## Mathematical content

- For a fixed variable list `P_1,\ldots,P_n` and a truth row, the truth-table row conjunction is the conjunction choosing `P_i` when the row makes `P_i` true and `\neg P_i` when the row makes `P_i` false.
- The truth-table row clause for a false row is the disjunction choosing `P_i` when the row makes `P_i` false and `\neg P_i` when the row makes `P_i` true, so the clause is false exactly on that row.
- Canonical DNF is the disjunction of the row conjunctions corresponding to the true rows of the formula.
- Canonical CNF is the conjunction of the row clauses corresponding to the false rows of the formula.
- Canonical DNF theorem: every formula is logically equivalent to its canonical DNF relative to a fixed ordering of its finitely many variables.
- Canonical CNF theorem: every formula is logically equivalent to its canonical CNF relative to a fixed ordering of its finitely many variables.
- Mention special cases: a contradiction has no true rows; a tautology has no false rows. Use the empty disjunction and empty conjunction conventions.

